# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flathead-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] A **2+2** (also **2-plus-2**) is a car-body style that has a seat each for the driver and front passenger, and two rear seats.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] The latter may be individual "bucket" seats, fold-downs, or a full-width "bucketed" bench seat, but always with less leg room than either the front seats or a standard two-door car.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] The style is different from four- or five-seat automobiles having normal-size rear seats, with second-row 2+2 seating typically only suitable for children or occasional use.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] By standard definition, all cars in the 2+2 category have two front seats and two rear seats.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] Other common characteristics for 2+2 cars include relatively little room for the rear passengers and a "streamlined" body with two doors.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] While 2+2 seating is most commonly associated with coupés, especially those which strongly favour front passenger seating such as sports cars and grand tourer, certain convertibles with "auxiliary"-type rear seats may also be regarded as 2+2s.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] Some vehicles (such as the TVR Cerbera and Toyota iQ) have been marketed as "3+1" due to their front passenger seat having more space for forward adjustment than the driver's, allowing for more leg room for one rear-seat passenger.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] There are many coupés which meet the definition of a 2+2 but are not described by their manufacturers as such.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] This is because the term *2+2* is most often used to distinguish cars with what typically amounts to auxiliary rear seating, at times enlarged from a two-seat version of the same model to accommodate it, such as the Jaguar E-type fixed-head coupé 2+2.
[src:flathead-engine/2-2-car-body-style] Other similar examples of stretched two-seaters include the Lotus Elan +2, Mazda RX-8, and Nissan 280ZX 2+2.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] The **A-segment** is the first category in the passenger car classification system defined by the European Commission.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] It is used for **city cars**, the smallest category of passenger cars defined.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] A-segment sales represented approximately 4.2% of the European market in 2024.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] It is approximately equivalent to the kei car class in Japan.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] As of 2021, the A-segment category size spans from approximately 2.7 metres (110 in) to 3.7 metres (150 in).
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Body styles for A-segment cars in Europe have historically nearly always been hatchbacks.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] But as crossovers gain popularity, new models have begun to shift to resemble crossovers.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Examples of crossover city cars include Suzuki Ignis and Toyota Aygo X.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Other body styles such as sedans have only a few models present in this segment because these shapes largely prove impractical at typical A-segment dimensions.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] A-segment cars are traditionally offered with manual transmission as the sole transmission option.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Beginning in the 2010s, automatic options are increasingly available.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Some newer models most often utilize CVTs, while a small number of manufacturers also offer automated manual transmissions.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] The engines of A-segment cars commonly range from 1.0 to 1.4 litres, either in inline-four or three configuration.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Newer models may have turbocharged and/or hybrid engines with a particular emphasis on higher fuel efficiency.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] In 2020 the ten highest selling A-segment cars in Europe were Fiat Panda, Fiat 500, Toyota Aygo, Renault Twingo, Volkswagen Up!, Hyundai i10, Kia Picanto, Peugeot 108, Citroën C1 and Suzuki Ignis.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] 2019 - In 2019, sales of minicars were down 2% compared to a total market gain of 1% which means this segment now makes up 7.7% of the total European car market at 1.21 million sales, down from 8% in 2018.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] And with margins on minicars under pressure due to increased costs to comply with stricter safety and emissions standards, manufacturers are scaling back investments in to minicars or switching to an EV-only strategy.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] In Italy, A-segment cars represented 16.4% of car sales in the first half of 2019.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] 2020 - European sales of minicars were down by a third in 2020, which translates to nearly 400,000 fewer sales and means the segment loses market share as the overall market is down 24%.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] As a result, this segment now makes up 6.8% of the total European car market, down from 7.7% last year.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] And their share is expected to shrink further in coming years, as manufacturers are pulling out of this segment or switching their models to EV-only.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] This is a result of increasing costs to comply with stricter safety and especially emissions standards, which makes minicars nearly unprofitable, especially considering that for most models from European brands this is the only market.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] In the United States, minicar segment cars represented 0.5% of the market share.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] In 2020 the highest selling minicar segment cars in the U.S. were the Chevrolet Spark, Mitsubishi Mirage and Mini Cooper.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] In India, historically the A-segment cars had the highest sales.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] Sales have been in decline in recent years, falling from 70,000 sales per month in 2014 to 47,000 sales per month in 2016.
[src:flathead-engine/a-segment] As of 2019, several A-segment cars had successes outside Europe, such as Hyundai Grand i10, Honda Brio, Kia Picanto, Tata Tiago, Toyota Wigo, Suzuki Celerio, Suzuki Wagon R, Suzuki/Maruti Alto, Ford Figo, Smart ForTwo, Citroën C1, Peugeot 108, and modern Fiat 500.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:flathead-engine/aero-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:flathead-engine/aeronca-e-107] The **Aeronca E-107** was one of the first low-cost reliable engines of the post-World War I era.
[src:flathead-engine/aeronca-e-107] The E-107A was a production aviation flathead engine designed to replace a Morehouse engine on the first prototype of the Aeronca C-2.
[src:flathead-engine/aeronca-e-107] The first five were produced without cooling fins on the crankcase, but with all versions having air-cooling fins atop the cylinder heads, similar to many air-cooled two-stroke engines in appearance.
[src:flathead-engine/aeronca-e-107] A Winfleld Model 5 carburetor was standard for the engine.
[src:flathead-engine/aeronca-e-107] The E-107 was replaced by the uprated, overhead valvetrain E-113 engine based on the same design.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] An **aircraft** is a vehicle that can fly by gaining support from the air.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] It counters the force of gravity by using either static lift or the dynamic lift of an airfoil, or, in a few cases, direct downward thrust from its engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Common examples of aircraft include airplanes, drones, rotorcraft (including helicopters), airships (including blimps), gliders, paramotors, and hot air balloons.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Part 1 (Definitions and Abbreviations) of Subchapter A of Chapter I of Title 14 of the U.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Code of Federal Regulations states that *aircraft* "means a device that is used or intended to be used for flight in the air".
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The human activity that surrounds aircraft is called *aviation*.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The science of aviation includes the designing and building of aircraft, which is called *aeronautics*. a *crewed* aircraft is flown by an onboard pilot, whereas an unmanned aerial vehicle may be remotely controlled or *autonomous*, controlled by onboard computers.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aircraft may be classified by different criteria, such as lift type, propulsion (if any), usage and others.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The history of aviation spans over two millennia, from the earliest innovations like kites and attempts at tower jumping to supersonic and hypersonic flight in powered, heavier-than-air jet aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Kite flying in China, dating back several hundred years BC, is considered the earliest example of man-made flight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In the 15th century, Leonardo da Vinci created flying machine designs incorporating aeronautical concepts, but they were unworkable due to the limitations of contemporary knowledge.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In the late 18th century, the Montgolfier brothers invented the hot-air balloon which soon led to manned flights.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] At almost the same time, the discovery of hydrogen gas led to the invention of the hydrogen balloon.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Various theories in mechanics by physicists during the same period, such as fluid dynamics and Newton's laws of motion, led to the development of modern aerodynamics; most notably by Sir George Cayley.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Balloons, both free-flying and tethered, began to be used for military purposes from the end of the 18th century, with France establishing balloon companies during the French Revolution.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In the 19th century, especially the second half, experiments with gliders provided the basis for learning the dynamics of winged aircraft; most notably by Cayley, Otto Lilienthal, and Octave Chanute.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] By the early 20th century, advances in engine technology and aerodynamics made controlled, powered, manned heavier-than-air flight possible for the first time.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In 1903, following their pioneering research and experiments with wing design and aircraft control, the Wright brothers successfully incorporated all of the required elements to create and fly the first airplane.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In 1906 Charles Frederick Page was granted the first U.S. patent for an aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The basic configuration with its characteristic cruciform tail was established by 1909, followed by rapid design and performance improvements aided by the development of more powerful engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The first vessels of the air were the rigid steerable balloons pioneered by Ferdinand von Zeppelin that became synonymous with airships and dominated long-distance flight until the 1930s, when large flying boats became popular for trans-oceanic routes.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] After World War II, the flying boats were in turn replaced by airplanes operating from land, made far more capable first by improved propeller engines, then by jet engines, which revolutionized both civilian air travel and military aviation.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In the latter half of the 20th century, the development of digital electronics led to major advances in flight instrumentation and "fly-by-wire" systems.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The 21st century has seen the widespread use of pilotless drones for military, commercial, and recreational purposes.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] With computerized controls, inherently unstable aircraft designs, such as flying wings, have also become practical.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft or *aerostats* use buoyancy to float in the air in much the same way that ships float on the water.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] They are characterized by one or more large cells or canopies, filled with a lifting gas such as helium, hydrogen or hot air, which is less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Other gases lighter than air also theoretically work; however, such gases also need to be safe for human use (non-flammable, non-toxic).
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Small hot-air balloons, called sky lanterns, were first invented in ancient China prior to the 3rd century BC and used primarily in cultural celebrations, although they also had military purposes.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] They, along with kites, were two forms of unmanned aircraft that originated from China.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Kites were also used in the military, but unlike sky lanterns, their flight is caused by the differences in air pressure beneath and above the kite.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A balloon was originally any aerostat, while the term airship was used for large, powered aircraft designs—usually fixed-wing.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In 1919, Frederick Handley Page was reported as referring to "ships of the air," with smaller passenger types as "Air yachts." In the 1930s, large intercontinental flying boats were also sometimes referred to as "ships of the air" or "flying-ships".
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft don't typically require a pilot's license in the United States.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In most countries in Europe, standards for flying Lighter-than-air aircraft tend to be stricter compared to the United States.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Heavier-than-air aircraft or *aerodynes* are denser than air and thus must find some way to obtain enough lift that can overcome the aircraft's weight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] There are two ways to produce dynamic upthrust—aerodynamic lift by having air flowing past an aerofoil (such dynamic interaction of aerofoils with air is the origin of the term "aerodyne"), or powered lift in the form of reactional lift from downward engine thrust.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aerodynamic lift involving wings is the most common, and can be achieved via two methods.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Fixed-wing aircraft (airplanes and gliders) achieve airflow past the wings by having the entire aircraft moving forward through the air, while rotorcraft (helicopters and autogyros) do so by having mobile, elongated wings spinning rapidly around a mast in an assembly known as the rotor.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Gliders were one of the first forms of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] They are a special type of aircraft that doesn't require an engine.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The first person to successfully build a human-carrying glider was George Cayley, who also was the first to discover the four major aerodynamic forces.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The first powered aircraft (Airplane) was invented by Wilbur and Orville Wright.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A *rotary-wing aircraft*, *rotorwing aircraft* or *rotorcraft* is a heavier-than-air aircraft with rotary wings that spin around a vertical mast to generate lift.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The assembly of several rotor blades mounted on a single mast is referred to as a rotor.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) defines a rotorcraft as "supported in flight by the reactions of the air on one or more rotors".
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Rotorcraft generally include aircraft where one or more rotors provide lift throughout the entire flight, such as helicopters, gyroplanes, autogyros, and gyrodynes.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Compound rotorcraft augment the rotor with additional thrust engines, propellers, or static lifting surfaces.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Some types, such as helicopters, are capable of vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] An aircraft that uses rotor lift for vertical flight but changes to solely fixed-wing lift in horizontal flight is not a rotorcraft but a convertiplane.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The largest aircraft by weight and largest regular fixed-wing aircraft ever built, as of 2016, was the Antonov An-225 *Mriya*.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] That Soviet-built (Ukrainian SSR) six-engine transport of the 1980s was 84 m (276 ft) long, with an 88 m (289 ft) wingspan.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] It holds the world payload record, after transporting 428,834 lb (194,516 kg) of goods, and has flown 100 t (220,000 lb) loads commercially.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] With a maximum loaded weight of 550–700 t (1,210,000–1,540,000 lb), it was also the heaviest aircraft built to date.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The aircraft was destroyed during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The largest military airplanes are the Ukrainian Antonov An-124 *Ruslan* (world's second-largest airplane, also used as a civilian transport), and American Lockheed C-5 Galaxy transport, weighing, loaded, over 380 t (840,000 lb).
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The fastest recorded powered aircraft flight and fastest recorded aircraft flight of an air-breathing powered aircraft was of the NASA X-43A *Pegasus*, a scramjet-powered, hypersonic, lifting body experimental research aircraft, at Mach 9.68 or 6,755 mph (10,870 km/h) on 16 November 2004.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Before the X-43A, the fastest recorded powered airplane flight, and still the record for the fastest manned powered airplane, was the North American X-15, rocket-powered airplane at Mach 6.7 or 7,274 km/h (4,520 mph) on 3 October 1967.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The fastest manned, air-breathing powered airplane is the Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird, a U.S. reconnaissance jet fixed-wing aircraft, having reached 3,530 km/h (2,193 mph) on 28 July 1976.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The main feature of unpowered aircraft is the inability to directly provide thrust through its engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] This means that all unpowered aircraft rely on the environment for sustained flight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Gliders, for example, take advantage of their aerodynamic properties to enable them to travel long distances.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Techniques such as thermal circling, where gliders fly into warm air which allows them to rise, prolong flight time.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Due to the lack of an engine, initial propulsion assistance is usually necessary to ensure flight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A common glider launching method is aerotowing, where another aircraft tows the glider to an altitude from which sustained flight is possible.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Steering for a glider is also rudimentary, while more complex gliders like sailplanes usually have joysticks for steering, more basic aircraft like hang gliders rely on the pilot's physical coordination to change the centre of gravity.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A powered aircraft is an aircraft with a source of mechanical power, used to produce thrust.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Such sources are generally engines, as is the case with airplanes, but can be human-powered in more extreme cases.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Propeller aircraft, as their name suggests, rely on propellers to produce thrust for the airplane.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Compared to engines using propellers, jet engines can provide much higher thrust, higher speeds and, above about 40,000 ft (12,000 m), greater efficiency.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Although some rotorcraft, such as rotor kites, can be unpowered, most rotorcraft are powered by either piston engines or turboprops.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Some rotorcraft, including autogyros and gyrodynes, are propelled by a conventional propeller or jet engine, with the rotor unpowered, but most modern rotorcraft have a powered rotor, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Autogyros and gyrodynes are steered using a rudder, similarly to propeller and jet aircraft, and rotorcraft with powered rotors, such as helicopters, turn by adjusting the pitch of the rotor cyclically, so that the rotors on one side produce more lift than the other.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Rotorcraft with powered rotors typically need a tail rotor to counter the rotational torque produced by the rotor, which can cause the helicopter to spin.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] An *aerostat* or *lighter-than-air aircraft* relies on buoyancy to maintain flight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aerostats include unpowered balloons (free-flying or tethered) and powered airships.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The relative density of an aerostat as a whole is lower than that of the surrounding atmospheric air (hence the name "lighter-than-air").
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Its main component is one or more gas capsules made of lightweight skins, containing a lifting gas (hot air, or any gas with lower density than air, typically hydrogen or helium) that displaces a large volume of air to generate enough buoyancy to overcome its own weight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Payload (passengers and cargo) can then be carried on attached components such as a basket, a gondola, a cabin or various hardpoints.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] With airships, which need to be able to fly against wind, the lifting gas capsules are often protected by a more rigid outer envelope or an airframe, with other gasbags such as ballonets to help modulate buoyancy.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aerostats are so named because they use aerostatic buoyant force that does not require any forward movement through the surrounding air mass, resulting in the inherent ability to levitate and perform vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] This contrasts with the heavier-than-air aerodynes that primarily use aerodynamic lift, which must have consistent airflow over an aerofoil (wing) surface to stay airborne.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The term has also been used in a narrower sense, to refer to the statically tethered balloon in contrast to the free-flying airship.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] This article uses the term in its broader sense.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] An *aerodyne* is a heavier-than-air aircraft that relies on aerodynamic lift, or upthrust produced by the airflow, to fly.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aerodynes include rotorcraft, airplanes, gliders, and several other varieties of aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Airplanes use wings, or airfoils, to direct the airflow to produce lift.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Wings are usually constructed with a wooden or metal inner framework, and a skin stretched over it.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Rotorcraft use a rotor which acts like a rotating wing, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] When aerodynes carry a payload, it is usually carried inside the aircraft's fuselage, or central structure, but aerodynes can also carry loads attached outside the aircraft or inside the wing.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Unlike aerostats, which control their altitude by changing their weight, aerodynes use control surfaces to control their altitude, or raise or lower the lift on their wing by adjusting their speed.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] As they typically travel at higher speeds than aerostats, most aerodynes have a rigid structure consisting of a frame covered by a skin.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Powered aircraft are typically powered by internal combustion engines (piston or turbine) burning fossil fuels—typically gasoline (avgas) or jet fuel.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A very few are powered by rocket power, ramjet propulsion, or by electric motors, or by internal combustion engines of other types, or using other fuels.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A very few have been powered, for short flights, by human muscle energy (e.g.: Gossamer Condor).
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The avionics comprise any *electronic* aircraft flight control systems and related equipment, including electronic cockpit instrumentation, navigation, radar, monitoring, and communications systems.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The flight envelope of an aircraft refers to its approved design capabilities in terms of airspeed, load factor and altitude.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The maximal total *range* is the maximum distance an aircraft can fly between takeoff and landing.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Powered aircraft range is limited by the aviation fuel energy storage capacity (chemical or electrical) considering both weight and volume limits.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Unpowered aircraft range depends on factors such as cross-country speed and environmental conditions.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The range can be seen as the cross-country ground speed multiplied by the maximum time in the air.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The fuel time limit for powered aircraft is fixed by the available fuel (considering reserve fuel requirements) and the rate of consumption.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The Airbus A350-900ULR is among the longest range airliners.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Some aircraft can gain energy while airborne through the environment (e.g. collecting solar energy or through rising air currents from mechanical or thermal lifting) or from in-flight refueling.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] These aircraft could theoretically have an infinite range.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Control systems adjust the orientation of a vehicle about its CG.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A control system includes control surfaces which, when deflected, generate a moment (or couple from ailerons) about the cg which rotates the aircraft in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] For example, a pitching moment comes from a force applied at a distance forward or aft of the cg, causing the aircraft to pitch up or down.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A fixed-wing aircraft increases or decreases the lift generated by the wings when it pitches nose up or down by increasing or decreasing the angle of attack (AOA).
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The roll angle is also known as bank angle on a fixed-wing aircraft, which usually "banks" to change the horizontal direction of flight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A fixed wing is typically unstable in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Pitch and yaw stabilities of conventional fixed wing designs require horizontal and vertical stabilisers, which act similarly to the feathers on an arrow.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] These stabilizing surfaces allow equilibrium of aerodynamic forces and to stabilise the flight dynamics of pitch and yaw.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In fixed-wing aircraft, multiple control surfaces are used to adjust the aircraft's roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Ailerons, hinged surfaces normally located on the rear edge of the wing, can raise or lower the lift produced by one side of the wing, causing the aircraft to bank to one side.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Elevators, usually located in the horizontal stabilizer, are used to increase or decrease the lift produced by the tail, causing the aircraft to pitch upwards or downwards, which in turn affects the lift of the wing.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] However, when the ailerons are used to turn an aircraft to the left, the right aileron must be tilted downwards, producing more drag than the left aileron and causing the aircraft to yaw right.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] To counteract this force, most fixed-wing aircraft have a rudder mounted on the vertical stabilizer which can deflect the airflow to the tail left or right to control the aircraft's yaw.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In rotorcraft, control is mainly accomplished through the cyclical tilting of the rotor's blades, increasing the angle of attack of the blades on one side and decreasing the angle of attack on the other.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Similarly to the rudder on fixed-wing aircraft, rotorcraft with powered rotors have a tail rotor, which counters the rotational thrust produced by the rotor and allows the aircraft to turn in forward flight.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Rotorcraft with unpowered rotors, such as autogyros, use a rudder for yaw.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aircraft engines produce gases, noise, and particulates from fossil fuel combustion, raising environmental concerns over their global effects and on local air quality.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Jet airliners contribute to climate change by emitting carbon dioxide (CO2), the best understood greenhouse gas, and, with less scientific understanding, nitrogen oxides, contrails and particulates.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Their radiative forcing is estimated at 1.4 that of CO2 alone, excluding induced cirrus cloud with a very low level of scientific understanding.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In 2018, global commercial operations generated 2.4% of CO2 emissions.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Jet airliners have become more fuel efficient and CO2 emissions per revenue ton-kilometer (RTK) in 2018 were 47% of those in 1990.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In 2018, CO2 emissions averaged 88 grams of CO2 per revenue passenger per km.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] While the aviation industry is more fuel efficient, overall emissions have risen as the volume of air travel has increased.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] By 2020, aviation emissions were 70% higher than in 2005 and they could grow by 300% by 2050.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aircraft noise pollution disrupts sleep, children's education and could increase cardiovascular risk.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Airports can generate water pollution due to their extensive handling of jet fuel and deicing chemicals if not contained, contaminating nearby water bodies.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aviation activities emit ozone and ultrafine particles, both of which are health hazards.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Piston engines used in general aviation burn Avgas, releasing toxic lead.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aviation's environmental footprint can be reduced by better fuel economy in aircraft, or air traffic control and flight routes can be optimized to lower non-CO2 effects on climate from NOx, particulates or contrails.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aviation biofuel, emissions trading and carbon offsetting, part of the ICAO's CORSIA, can lower CO2 emissions.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Aviation usage can be lowered by short-haul flight bans, train connections, personal choices and aviation taxation and subsidies.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Fuel-powered aircraft may be replaced by hybrid electric aircraft and electric aircraft or by hydrogen-powered aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Since 2021, the IATA members plan to achieve net-zero carbon emissions by 2050, followed by the ICAO in 2022.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] A military aircraft is any aircraft that is operated by a legal or insurrectionary armed service of any type.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Although scheduled air transport is the larger operation in terms of passenger numbers, GA is larger in the number of flights (and flight hours, in the U.S.) In the U.S., GA carries 166 million passengers each year, more than any individual airline, though less than all the airlines combined.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Since 2004, the U.S. airlines combined have carried over 600 million passengers each year, and in 2014, they carried a combined 662,819,232 passengers.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] All scheduled air transport is commercial, but general aviation can be either commercial or private.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Normally, the pilot, aircraft, and operator must all be authorized to perform commercial operations through separate commercial licensing, registration, and operation certificates.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] An *experimental aircraft* is an aircraft intended for testing new aerospace technologies and design concepts.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The term *research aircraft* or *testbed aircraft*, by contrast, generally denotes aircraft modified to perform scientific studies, such as weather research or geophysical surveying, similar to a research vessel.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] The term "experimental aircraft" also has specific legal meaning in Australia, the United States and some other countries; usually used to refer to aircraft flown with an experimental certificate.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] In the United States, this also includes most homebuilt aircraft, many of which are based on conventional designs and hence are experimental only in name because of certain restrictions in operation.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Model aircraft are typically small-scale replicas of flying aircraft, or new designs built smaller than most passenger aircraft.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Static model aircraft, which cannot fly, are usually not considered to be aircraft, but they can be used to test aspects of a flying aircraft, such as its aerodynamics.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Flying models are commonly propelled by electric motors, combustion engines, or are gliders, but there are many alternate methods of propulsion, such as wound rubber bands and small jet engines.
[src:flathead-engine/aircraft] Most flying model aircraft are either radio-controlled aircraft, fly freely, or are controlled by wires held by the pilot.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As the name implies, it is designed to handle a wider variety of terrain than most other vehicles.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It is street-legal in some countries, but not in most states, territories and provinces of Australia, the United States, and Canada.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] By the current ANSI definition, ATVs are intended for use by a single operator, but some ATVs, referred to as tandem ATVs, have been developed for use by the driver and one passenger.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The rider sits on and operates these vehicles like a motorcycle, but the extra wheels give more stability at slower speeds.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Although most are equipped with three or four wheels, six or eight wheel (tracked) models exist and have existed historically for specialized applications.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Multiple-user analogues with side-by-side seating are called utility terrain vehicles (UTVs) or side-by-sides to distinguish the classes of vehicle.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Both classes tend to have similar powertrain parts.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Engine sizes of ATVs for sale in the United States as of 2008 ranged from 49 to 1,000 cc (3.0 to 61 cu in).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Royal Enfield built and sold the first powered four-wheeler in 1893.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It had many bicycle components, including handlebars.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The Royal Enfield resembles a modern ATV-style quad bike but was designed as a form of horseless carriage for road use.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] With the introduction of straddle ridden ATVs, the term AATV was introduced to define the original amphibious ATV category.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The first three-wheeled ATV was the Sperry-Rand Tricart.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It was designed in 1967 as a graduate project of John Plessinger at the Cranbrook Academy of Arts near Detroit.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The Tricart was straddle-ridden with a sit-in rather than sit-on style (similar to the contemporaneous Big Wheel toy).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1968 Plessinger sold the Tricart patents and design rights to Sperry-Rand New Holland who manufactured them commercially.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Numerous small American manufacturers of 3-wheelers followed.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] These small manufacturers were unable to compete when larger motorcycle companies like Honda entered the market in 1969.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda introduced their first sit-on straddle-ridden three-wheeled all-terrain vehicle in 1969, known as a US90, as a 1970 Model.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Variations would be popularized in the James Bond movie, *Diamonds Are Forever* and TV shows such as *Doctor Who*, *Magnum, P.I.* and *Hart to Hart*.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1973, Honda trademarked the term "**All Terrain Cycle**" (ATC), applying it to all Honda's three-wheeled ATVs; it became a universal name associated with all vehicles of this type.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It was directly influenced by earlier 6-wheeled AATVs of the sixties, and utilized balloon tires for both a low environmental impact and to compensate for a lack of mechanical suspension.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda entered the 1980s with a virtual monopoly in the market, due to effective patents on design and engine placement.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] By 1980, other companies paid patent royalties to Honda to enter the lucrative ATC field with their own machines.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Yamaha introduced their first ATC, the Tri-Moto YZ125.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Kawasaki followed suit the next year with the KLT200, while Suzuki produced their first model, the ALT125, in 1982.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As the popularity of ATCs increased dramatically, rapid development ensued.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The ability to go anywhere on terrain that most other vehicles could not cross soon made them popular with US and Canadian hunters.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As other manufacturers were entering the market, Honda was diversifying, offering the ATC250R, the first Sport ATC intended for competition, in 1981.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The 1982 Honda ATC200E Big Red was a landmark model.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It featured both suspension and racks, making it the first ATC designed specifically for utility, and would become the world's best-selling ATC.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda followed that effort in 1983 with the ATC200X, an easy-to-handle 192 cc (0.192 L; 11.7 cu in) four-stroke Sport ATC that was ideal for new riders.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Not to be outdone, Kawasaki and Yamaha responded with their own Sport ATCs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] 1984 saw the release of the Kawasaki KXT250 Tecate, and Yamaha followed in 1985 with the Tri-Z 250.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Both were liquid cooled 250 cc two-strokes capable of giving the Honda ATC250R competition.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In response to growing market, American Specialty manufacturer Tiger also introduced a series of ATCs, hand-built-to-order models that included the Tiger 500, the largest displacement ATC produced commercially.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While Kawasaki and Yamaha both produced utility ATCs, famously making the KLT 250 Police and Yamahauler respectively, Suzuki turned their attention to building Sport Quads.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda continued to diversify their line-up (at peak offering 10 distinct models), releasing the larger, fully suspended 250 cc Big Red utility ATC, and introduced the 350X Sport ATC, their largest displacement machine, in 1985.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] But the bulk of their sales were the 200cc line, offering six models and selling over 500,000 units in 3 years.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda's response to the Tecate and Tri-Z, the liquid cooled 1985 and 1986 ATC250R, remains one of the most desirable ATCs of the era, and aftermarket support still follows the machine.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] American-based manufacturers also produced ATCs in this period, albeit in small numbers.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Polaris offered the Scrambler in 1985 and 1986, producing appx 1600 units.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Speciality manufacturer Tiger ATV also produced a range of ATCs, but their liquidation in 1991 left no official record of how many units were produced.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The collector ATV market estimates vary drastically, from 300 to as many as 1000 units total production.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Tiger ATCs were offered for three years, with models using 80 to 500 cc (0.0800 to 0.500 L; 4.88 to 30.5 cu in) two-stroke engines provided by KTM and Rotax.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The Tiger 500 is notable for being the fastest consumer ATC available, with tested top speeds of +80 mph from the stock 42 horsepower (31.3 kW)@6500rpm engine and 5 speed gearbox.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] With final drive gearing changes, the ATC could exceed 100 mph.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] However, due to the rarity of the machines the brand never became well-known, and as all Tiger Models were custom-ordered and built to the buyer's specifications for the purpose of factory ATV racing, Polaris is generally known as the first American 'Production' ATV producer.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Production of three-wheelers was voluntarily ceased by all manufacturers by 1987, in light of safety concerns, and ahead of any legislation.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Though later studies showed that three-wheelers were not considered more unstable than four-wheelers (although accidents are equally severe in both classes), manufacturers agreed to a 10-year moratorium on production, and to collectively financing a +US$100 million ATV safety campaign.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Despite the moratorium lifting, manufacturers did not return to the ATC market, focusing instead on four-wheeled ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] A ban on sales of new or used three-wheelers and a recall of all remaining three-wheelers was proposed by the American Academy of Pediatrics.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] These safety issues with three-wheel ATCs caused a shift in the buying public, as the sales of later four-wheel ATV models grew rapidly.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While three-wheel models ended production in 1987, agreements between the major manufacturers and the US U.S.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Consumer Product Safety Commission to officially cease production and finance safety campaigns moved forward.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While the lighter weight of ATCs made them popular with certain riders, manufacturers continued to focus on ATV production.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] US Public Law 110-314, enacted on August 8, 2008, separated ATCs from existing new production ATV safety standards, and requires new standards for three-wheeled ATCs to be drafted.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This effectively suspended importation of three-wheeled ATCs, until new standards of safety can be drafted.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As of 2020, such standards have not been drafted.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While search engines can find informal information suggesting major Japanese manufacturers pressed for this measure due to an influx of inexpensive Chinese ATCs in the American market, no official documentation or cited sources support these claims.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Currently, all manufacturers not based in the US are restricted from the manufacture and sale of new Three-Wheeled All Terrain Cycles, until safety standards can be implemented.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Below is a summary of Section 232, which effects the ATC ban.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Suzuki was a leader in the development of mass production four-wheeled ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It sold the first model, the 1982 QuadRunner LT125, which was a recreational machine for beginners.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Adventure Vehicles of Monroe, Louisiana made the first quad ATV in 1980.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It was a rudimentary vehicle reminiscent of the Tote Gote of the 1960s.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Suzuki sold the first four-wheeled mini ATV, the LT50, from 1984 to 1987.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] After the LT50, Suzuki sold the first ATV with a CVT transmission, the LT80, from 1987 to 2006.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1985 Suzuki introduced to the industry the first high-performance four-wheel ATV, the Suzuki LT250R QuadRacer.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This machine was in production for the 1985–1992 model years.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] During its production run, it underwent three major engineering makeovers.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] However, the core features were retained.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] These were: a sophisticated long-travel suspension, a liquid-cooled, two-stroke motor, and a fully-manual five-speed transmission (for 1985–1986 models), and a six-speed transmission (for the '87–'92 models).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It was a machine exclusively designed for racing by highly skilled riders.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda responded a year later with the FourTrax TRX250R—a machine that has not been replicated until recently.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It currently remains a trophy winner and competitor to big-bore ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Kawasaki responded with its Tecate-4 250.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The TRX250R was very similar to the ATC250R it eventually replaced and is often considered one of the greatest sport ATVs ever built.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1987, Yamaha Motor Company introduced a different type of high-performance machine, the Banshee 350, which featured a twin-cylinder liquid-cooled two-stroke motor from the RD350LC street motorcycle.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Heavier and more difficult to ride in the dirt than the 250s, the Banshee became a popular machine with sand dune riders thanks to its unique power delivery.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The Banshee remains popular, but 2006 is the last year it was available in the U.S.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] (due to EPA emissions regulations); it remained available in Canada until 2008 and in Australia until 2012.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The Warrior 350 was introduced in 1987 and went on for years as a light and fast ATV.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Shortly after the introduction of the Banshee in 1987, Suzuki released the LT500R QuadRacer.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This unique quad was powered by a 500 cc liquid-cooled two-stroke engine with a five-speed transmission.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This ATV earned the nickname "Quadzilla" with its remarkable amount of speed and size.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While there are claims of 100+ mph (160 km/h) stock Quadzillas, it was officially recorded by 3&4 Wheel Action magazine as reaching a top speed of over 79 mph (127 km/h) in a high-speed shootout in its 1988 June issue, making it the fastest production four-wheeled ATV ever produced.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Suzuki discontinued the production of the LT500R in 1990 after just four years.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] At the same time, the development of utility ATVs was rapidly escalating.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The 1986 Honda FourTrax TRX350 4x4 ushered in the era of four-wheel-drive ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Other manufacturers quickly followed suit, and 4x4s have remained the most popular type of ATV ever since.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] These machines are popular with hunters, farmers, ranchers, and workers at construction sites.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Models are divided into the sport and utility markets.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Sport models are generally small, light, two-wheel-drive vehicles that accelerate quickly, have a manual transmission, and run at speeds up to approximately 80 mph (130 km/h).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Utility models are generally bigger four-wheel-drive vehicles with a maximum speed of up to approximately 70 mph (110 km/h).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] They can haul small loads on attached racks or small dump beds, and tow small trailers.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Due to the different weights, each has advantages on different types of terrain.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] A popular model is Yamaha's Raptor 700, which has a nearly 700 cc four-stroke engine.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Six-wheel models often have a small dump bed, with an extra set of wheels at the back to increase the payload capacity.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] They can be either four-wheel-drive (back wheels driving only), or six-wheel-drive.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 2011 LandFighter was founded, "the first Dutch/European ATV brand".
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Most production is in Taiwan, to European standards; the ATVs are finally assembled in the Netherlands.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Safety helmets, mandatory in some jurisdictions, provide the rider with some protection in the case of an accident.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Safety courses and educational literature reduced the number and severity of accidents among ATC and ATV riders.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As cornering is more challenging on a three-wheel ATC than with a four-wheeled machine, properly leaning into the turn is required to counterbalance the weight and keep the machine stable.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Careless operators may roll over at high speeds.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The lighter front-end and smaller footprint of ATCs present both a flipping and steering hazard under acceleration and on inclines.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Lateral rollovers may also occur when traversing steep inclines.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Four-wheel quad cycles have a tendency to roll over, often injuring or killing the rider.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Suitably designed roll bars can be fitted, which do not prevent the cycle from overturning, but prop it up, providing some protection for the rider.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Safety has been a major issue with ATVs due to the many deaths and injuries associated with them and the lack of protection due to the absence of a rigid cab.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Modern ATVs were introduced in the early 1970s, with almost immediate alarming injury rates for children and adolescents.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Based on analysis of the National Trauma Data Bank, ATVs are more dangerous than dirt bikes, possibly due to crush injuries and failure to wear safety gear such as helmets.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] They are as dangerous as motorcycles, based on mortality and injury scores.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] More children and women, who are less likely to wear helmets, are injured on ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Many common injuries can be prevented with the use of proper protective equipment.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Most ATV manufacturers recommend at least a suitable DOT-approved helmet, protective eyewear, gloves and suitable riding boots for all riding conditions.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Sport or aggressive riders, or riders on challenging terrain (such as those rock crawling or hillclimbing), may opt for a motocross-style chest protector and knee/shin guards for further protection.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Use of tires suited to a particular terrain can also play a vital role in preventing injuries.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Fatal accidents typically occur when the vehicle rolls over.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Wearing a helmet can reduce the risk of death by 42% and the risk of nonfatal head injury by 64%.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] From 2016 to 2018, 1591 people died in ATV-associated incidents, with 28% involving children and youth under age 25.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Focus has shifted to machine size balanced with the usage of ATVs categorized by age ranges and engine displacements—in line with the consent decrees.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs are mandated to bear a label from the manufacturer stating that the use of machines greater than 90 cc by riders under the age of 12 is prohibited.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This is a 'manufacturer/CPSC recommendation' and not necessarily state law.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Although youth-sized ATVs are designed and available for younger riders, there are serious concerns regarding their appropriateness and safety for youth.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The American Academy of Pediatrics and the CPSC recommended that children under the age of 16 should not ride ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In the United States, about 40,000 children under age 16 are treated in emergency departments for ATV-related injuries each year.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] A Canadian study stated that "associated injury patterns, severity, and costs to the healthcare system" of pediatric injuries associated to ATVs resemble those caused by motor vehicles, and that public policies should reflect this.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Helmets are underutilized and result in Glasgow Coma Scale scores in children presenting from ATV accidents being similar to those in motorcycle accidents.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The Consumer Product Safety Commission met in March 2005 to discuss the dangers of ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Data from 2004 showed 44,000 injuries and almost 150 fatalities in children while riding ATVs.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In response to calls for further regulation, the CPSC's director of compliance, John Gibson Mullan, said that because the statistics were not rising, existing measures were working.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] *The New York Times* reported an accusation from a staff member that Mullan, who had previously worked as a lawyer for the ATV industry, had distorted the statistics and prevented further debate.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1988, the All-terrain Vehicle Safety Institute (ASI) was formed to provide training and education for ATV riders.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The cost of attending the training is minimal and is free for purchasers of new machines that fall within the correct age and size guidelines.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Successful completion of a safety training class is, in many states, a minimum requirement for minors to be granted permission to ride on public land.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Some states have had to implement their own safety training programs, as the ASI program cannot include those riders with ATVs outside of the age and size guidelines, which may still fall within the states' laws.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] From January 1, 2019, the United States Consumer Product Safety Commission updated ATV lighting requirements, requiring all categories of ATVs to be equipped with a stop lamp and side reflectors similar to those required on passenger cars.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In industry, agriculture workers are disproportionately at risk for ATV accidents.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Most fatalities occur in white men over the age of 55.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATV's have the ability to be officially street legal and can be used on at least certain roads in 21 states, requirements vary by state however.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] A "quad" is recognised by UK law as a vehicle with four wheels and a mass of less than 550 kg (1,210 lb).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] A quad cycle to be used on a public road in the UK must be taxed, insured and registered, and the driver must have a category B (car) or B1 (motor vehicles with 4 wheels up to 400 kg unladen or 550 kg if designed for carrying goods) licence.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In the United Kingdom, the safety issues of cars classed as quad cycles are illustrated by the case of the G-Wiz (REVAi).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The electric microcar was given a Euro NCAP specification test, and the results showed that the vehicle's occupants would suffer "serious or life-threatening" injuries in a 64 km/h (40 mph) crash.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The UK Department for Transport concluded that there were serious safety concerns when the REVA was crashed at 35 mph (56 km/h).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] After consultation with stakeholders including farmers and quad cycle manufacturers, Australia's Heads of Workplace Safety Authorities (HWSA) in 2011 released a strategy intended to reduce the number of deaths and serious injuries associated with quad-bike use.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The development of the report was closely followed by *The Weekly Times* newspaper and ABC television which reviewed the issue through its *7.30* program.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] When the report was released the only model of anti-crush protection on the market was the Australian-made "Quadbar", which was vigorously opposed by the industry through media activity and a poster campaign at regional events for farmers which are often used to showcase new products.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The industry argued that the device had not been properly tested and that past studies of tractor-style ROPS such as a full-frame 'cage' around the operator were not only ineffective, but could add to the risk to injury or death.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In February 2012, the Melbourne-based Institute for Safety, Compensation and Recovery Research (ISCRR) published a paper which criticised the research claims of the manufacturers in relation to crush protection devices.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The paper reviewed research in a number of countries since 1993 in relation to rollover protection and found that the industry's opposition to rollover protection could not be supported because of limitations in past research.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] It recommended further research on the topic and the development of research tools based on the use of ATV/quadbikes in Australian conditions.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In most provinces, ATV users are required to register their vehicle and have a designated off-highway license plate.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Some provinces, like Nova Scotia, recently moved to allow ATVs limited road shoulder usage for the purpose of travelling from one trailhead to another.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In Germany the legal situation is very unrestrictive, but complex.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Almost, if not any manufacturer ATV registered at the KBA (Kraftfahrtbundesamt) can be registered for road use in Germany.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Vehicle-taxes, insurance and a number plate as well as a MOT (TÜV) are required.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Quads can be accredited in two different ways in Germany.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Usually they are taxed and insured as a regular automobile, which results in the tax being calculated by emissions and displacement in 100ccm steps.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs registered as an automobile have to be restricted to a power output of 20 hp/15 kW and are allowed to be driven with a passenger, provided a passenger seat is registered in the vehicle papers.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The quad must have at least one rear mirror on the left side, minimum 10x5cm.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The vehicle must have a high-/low-beam headlight, brake light, indicators, a number plate mount on front and back, and a horn.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs under 400 kilograms (880 lb) do not need a reverse gear.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Over 400 kilograms (880 lb) empty weight, a reverse gear and reverse light are required.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The maximum engine noise restrictions depend on date of first registration and engine displacement.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] On the other hand, ATVs can be registered "as agricultural and silvicultural" (LoF/Land- oder Forstwirtschaftlich) giving the owner some benefits: The quad can be driven with power outputs more than 20 hp and tax is much cheaper, being calculated by empty weight.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The insurance cost is much lower than for other agricultural vehicles and ATVs,.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Custom builds and engine replacements are possible to get street legal, by undergoing a single-acceptance procedure from the MOT(TÜV).
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This results in some custom quads popularly sporting 4-cycle motorcycle engines street legal.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] A common example are Yamaha Raptor 700 Conversions to a Yamaha 1000 cc engine from the early Yamaha Fazer and R1.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVS are mostly treated as a regular automobile in Germany, which means no special-vehicle or motorcycle licence is needed.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The regular driving license class B (multiple track motorised vehicles up to 3.5 tons) is sufficient even for LoF registered vehicles.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Consequently, until 2013, quads could be driven only by people at least 18 years old with a drivers license.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] People under 18 may have a 50 cc or 125 cc bike license, but this does not allow them to drive quad bikes.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As quad bikes were treated as automobiles, wearing a helmet was not required until January 2006, when helmets became required for ATVs, three-wheelers, trikes, etc.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] No additional protective gear is required.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Officially, driving a quad requires the owner to always carry a hazard triangle and a first-aid kit, and a reflective vest if the quad is registered as an agricultural vehicle.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Due to the lack of storage room, police usually don't check the back of the vehicle, but if they lack the required equipment, they may be prosecuted.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs accounted for 58% of the SI (spark ignited) recreational vehicles in the US in the year 2000.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] That year, recreational SI vehicles produced 0.16% of NOx, 8% of HC, 5% of CO and 0.8% of PM emissions for all vehicles, both highway and nonroad.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] As a point of comparison, the nonroad SI < 19 kW (~25 hp) category (small spark ignition engines such as lawnmowers) comprised 20% of HC and 23% of CO total emissions.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While recreational SI vehicles produce an aggregate of <4% of all HC emissions in the US, based on the relatively small population of ATVs (<1.2M) and small annual usage (<350 hrs), EPA emission regulations now include such engines, starting with the model year 2006.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Engines meeting these standards now produce only 3% of the HC emissions that previously unregulated engines did.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] While the deep treads on some ATV tires are effective for navigating rocky, muddy and root covered terrain, these treads are also capable of digging channels that may drain bogs, increase sedimentation in streams at crossings and damage groomed snowmobile trails.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Proper trail construction techniques can mitigate these effects.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In some countries where fencing is not common, such as the US, Canada and Australia, some ATV riders knowingly cross privately owned property in rural areas and travel over public or private properties, although only permitted on trails.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Subsequently, environmentalists criticize ATV riding as a sport for excessive use in areas which biologists consider to be sensitive, especially wetlands and sand dunes and in much of inland Australia.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Because both scientific studies and U.S.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] National Forest Service personnel have identified unregulated Off-Road Vehicles (ORVs) as the source of major detrimental impacts on national forests, the U.S.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Forest Service is currently engaged in the Travel Management Process, wherein individual forests are restricting all off-road motorized travel to approved trails and roads.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] This is in contrast to its previously allowed, unregulated cross-country travel across all national forest lands, except for specifically designated wilderness areas.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs using tracks instead of wheels are used at France's Cap Prudhomme in Antarctica.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs are also used in agriculture to bridge the advantages of trucks and tractors.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] They are used in a variety of industries for their maneuverability and off-roading ability.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Sport models are built with performance, rather than utility, in mind.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] To be successful at fast trail riding, an ATV must have light weight, high power, good suspension and a low center of gravity.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] These machines can be modified for such racing disciplines as motocross, woods racing (also known as cross country), desert racing (also known as Hare Scrambles), hill climbing, ice racing, speedway, Tourist Trophy (TT), flat track, drag racing and others.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Throughout the United States and the United Kingdom there are many quad racing clubs with enduro and quadcross sections.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] GNCC Racing began around 1980 and includes hare scramble and enduro type races.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] To date, events are mainly held in the eastern part of the United States.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] GNCC racing features many types of obstacles such as, hill climbing, creek and log crossings, dirt roads and wooded trails.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATV National Motocross Championship was formed around 1985.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVMX events are hosted at premiere motocross racetracks throughout the United States.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVMX consists of several groups, including the Pro (AMA Pro) and Amateur (ATVA) series.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Friday involves amateur practicing and racing on Saturday and Sunday.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Saturday also involves racing for the Pro Am Women and Pro Am Unlimited classes.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Sunday involves racing for the Pro and Pro Am production ATVs, but are scored separately.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] On average weekend over 500 racers will compete.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The FIM organizes the Quadcross of Nations at the end of the year.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The competition involves teams of three riders representing their nations.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] There are three motos with two riders of each nation competing per moto.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The location of the event changes from year to year.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Championship Mud Racing/CMR saw its infancy in 2006 as leaders of the ATV industry recognized a need for uniformity of classes and rules of various local mud bog events.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Providing standardized rules created the need for a governing body that both racers and event promoters could turn to and CMR was born.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Once unified, a true points series was established and lead to a national championship for what was once nothing more than a hobby for most.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 2007 the finalized board of directors was established and the first races were held in 2008.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Currently, the CMR schedule includes eight competition dates spanning from March to November.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Points are awarded throughout the season in several different competition classes of ATV and SxS Mud Racing.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The 2008 year included Mud Bog and Mudda-Cross competitions, but the 2009 and future seasons will only have Mudda-Cross competitions.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Classes range from 0–499 cc to a Super-Modified class which will allow any size ATV in competition.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] In 2005 the FIM Cross-Country Rallies World Championship started with a Quad Championship and the Dakar Rally added the Quad category in 2008.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Because the 2008 Dakar Rally was cancelled, the 2009 Dakar Rally was the first Dakar Rally with Quads.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Amateur and professional three-wheeler racing across the United States has also spiked in popularity once again, at levels not seen since the factory teams raced in the 1980s.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Part of the appeal is the cheapness of parts, and how easy it is to get into.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Races are held at various local and large venues, particularly in Ohio, New York, Pennsylvania, Arizona, Michigan and California.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Payouts are sometimes awarded to winners.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Each year in June, the world's biggest three-wheeler gathering is held at Haspin Acres, in Laurel, Indiana, for the Trikefest event.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Over the course of 3 days complete with camping, hundreds of people gather for the event which features competitive racing such as MX style racing, drag racing, mud racing, hill climbs and other events.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] For those who wish not to compete, there are also many trails a person can ride. as many as 100 or more three-wheelers show up each year, some built and restored to be raffled off, others brought to ride.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The fastest speed recorded on a quad cycle, or ATV given a flying start, is 315.74 km/h (196.19 mph), by Terry Wilmeth (USA), at the Madras Airport in Madras, Oregon, USA, on 15 June 2008.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] The other major discovery was also made in 2021 by an Engineering student Mr.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] Sajith Sajeev Bindhu from UKF College of Engineering from India has been done, it was about the discovery of ATV rear suspension into A design and the research which helps to improve the stability of ATV into a better format.
[src:flathead-engine/all-terrain-vehicle] That was the latest major change that concluded in the era of ATV .
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] A **flathead engine**, also known as a **sidevalve engine** or **valve-in-block engine**, is an internal combustion engine with its poppet valves contained within the engine block, instead of in the cylinder head, as in an overhead valve engine.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Flatheads were widely used internationally by automobile manufacturers from the late 1890s until the mid-1960s but were replaced by more efficient overhead valve and overhead camshaft engines.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] They are currently experiencing a revival in low-revving aero-engines such as the D-Motor.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The valve gear comprises a camshaft sited low in the cylinder block which operates the poppet valves via tappets and short pushrods (or sometimes with no pushrods at all).
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The flathead system obviates the need for further valvetrain components such as lengthy pushrods, rocker arms, overhead valves or overhead camshafts.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The sidevalves are typically adjacent, sited on one side of the cylinder(s), though some flatheads employ the less common "crossflow" "T-head" variant.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] In a T-head engine, the exhaust gases leave on the opposite side of the cylinder from the intake valve.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The sidevalve engine's combustion chamber is not above the piston (as in an OHV (overhead valve) engine) but to the side, above the valves.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The spark plug may be sited over the piston (as in an OHV engine) or above the valves; but aircraft designs with two plugs per cylinder may use either or both positions.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] "Pop-up pistons" may be used with compatible heads to increase compression ratio and improve the combustion chamber's shape to prevent knocking.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] "Pop-up" pistons are so called because, at top dead centre, they protrude above the top of the cylinder block.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The advantages of a sidevalve engine include simplicity, reliability, low part count, low cost, low weight, compactness, responsive low-speed power, low mechanical engine noise, and insensitivity to low-octane fuel.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The absence of a complicated valvetrain allows a compact engine that is cheap to manufacture, since the cylinder head may be little more than a simple metal casting.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] These advantages explain why side valve engines were used for passenger cars for many years, while OHV designs came to be specified only for high-performance applications such as aircraft, luxury cars, sports cars, and some motorcycles.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] At top dead centre, the piston gets very close to the flat portion of the cylinder head above, and the resultant squish turbulence produces excellent fuel/air mixing.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] A feature of the sidevalve design (particularly beneficial for an aero-engine) is that if a valve should seize in its guide and remain partially open, the piston would not be damaged, and the engine would continue operating safely on its other cylinders.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The main disadvantages of a sidevalve engine are poor gas flow, poor combustion chamber shape, and low compression ratio, all of which result in a low-revving engine with low power output and low efficiency.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Because sidevalve engines do not burn the fuel efficiently, they suffer from high hydrocarbon emissions.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Sidevalve engines can only be used for engines operating on the Otto principle.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The combustion chamber shape is unsuitable for Diesel engines, which require a high compression ratio for ignition to occur.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] In a sidevalve engine, intake and exhaust gases follow a circuitous route, with low volumetric efficiency, or "poor breathing", not least because the exhaust gases interfere with the incoming charge.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Because the exhaust follows a lengthy path to leave the engine, there is a tendency for the engine to overheat.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] High volumetric efficiency was less important for early cars because their engines rarely sustained extended high speeds, but designers seeking higher power outputs had to abandon the sidevalve.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] A compromise used by the Willys Jeep, Rover, Land Rover, and Rolls-Royce in the 1950s was the "F-head" (or "intake-over-exhaust" valving), which has one sidevalve and one overhead valve per cylinder.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The flathead's elongated combustion chamber is prone to preignition (or "knocking") if compression ratio is increased, but improvements such as laser ignition or microwave enhanced ignition might help prevent knocking.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Turbulence grooves may increase swirl inside the combustion chamber, thus increasing torque, especially at low rpm.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Better mixing of the fuel/air charge improves combustion and helps to prevent knocking.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] An advance in flathead technology resulted from experimentation in the 1920s by Sir Harry Ricardo, who improved their efficiency after studying the gas-flow characteristics of sidevalve engines.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The difficulty in designing a high-compression-ratio flathead means that most tend to be spark-ignition designs, and flathead diesels are virtually unknown.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The sidevalve arrangement was especially common in the United States and used for motor vehicle engines, even for engines with high specific power output.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Sidevalve designs are still common for many small single-cylinder or twin-cylinder engines, such as lawnmowers, rotavators, two-wheel tractors and other basic farm machinery.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Multicylinder flathead engines were used for cars such as the Ford Model T and Ford Model A, the Ford flathead V8 engine and the Ford Sidevalve engine.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Cadillac produced V-16 flathead engines for their Series 90 luxury cars from 1938 to 1940.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Packard and Pontiac produced flathead inline 8-cylinder engines until 1954.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Also in the British Morris Eight, and Morris Minor series I.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] After WWII, flathead designs began to be superseded by OHV (overhead valve) designs.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Flatheads were no longer common in cars, but they continued in more rudimentary vehicles such as off-road military Jeeps.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] In US custom car and hot rod circles, restored examples of early Ford flathead V8s are still seen.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The simplicity, lightness, compactness and reliability might seem ideal for an aero-engine, but because of their low efficiency, early flathead engines were deemed unsuitable.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Two notable exceptions were the American Aeronca E-107 opposed twin aero engine of 1930 and the Continental A40 flat four of 1931, which became one of the most popular light aircraft engines of the 1930s.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Two modern flatheads are the Belgian D-Motor flat-fours and flat-sixes.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] These are extremely oversquare and compact aero-engines with direct drive to a propeller.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] Flathead designs have been used on a number of early pre-war motorcycles, in particular US V-twins such as Harley-Davidson and Indian, some British singles, BMW flat twins and Russian copies thereof.
[src:flathead-engine/flathead-engine] The Cleveland Motorcycle Manufacturing Company produced a T-head four-cylinder in-line motorcycle engine in the 1920s.
